1. e4 e6 2. Nc3 {Usually White plays 2.d4 and only then 3.Nc3, but this move order is pretty common as well.} 2... d5 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. d4 {
Now we are back in the normal French Defense lines.} 5... c5 {Black attacks White's central pawn chain at the base.} 6. dxc5 Nc6 {By putting
pressure on White's e-pawn, Black more or less forces White to bring out his Bishop to f4. That is not a bad move, but it does limit White's options a bit.}
7. Bf4 Nxc5 {There is nothing wrong with the other capture, but this move is interesting and creates problems for White to solve immediately.} 8. Qd2 a6 9.
O-O-O $6 {It is a mistake for White to commit his King so soon to the queenside, where Black can fling forward his pawns and drive White's pieces
away from the defense of the King. In just a few moves, White's position is critical.} 9... b5 10. h4 (10. Bg5 {is covered in the game Kalinina-Drasko, Cappelle la Grande 2013.}) 10... b4 $1 {Black drives White's Knight away from the control of the e4 square.} 11. Ne2 Ne4 $1 {Perfect! The Knight settles in on e4, attacking both the Queen and the pawn on f2.} 12. Qe3 {White has to move the Queen somewhere.} 12... Qa5 {Black continues to bring out pieces with a gain of time. This move puts the
Queen on a very active square, but it also attacks the undefended pawn on a2.} 13. Kb1 {Again, White does not have much choice.} 13... Bc5 14. Nfd4 Nxd4 15.
Nxd4 Rb8 (15... Nc3+ $1 {already works:} 16. bxc3 bxc3 17. Nb3 (17. Rd3 Rb8+ 18. Kc1 {and now Black has various ways to win, such as} (18. Ka1 $4 {
gets mated immediately:} 18... Rb2 $1 19. Rxc3 Qxa2#) 18... Qb6 19. Kd1 Bd7 20. Ke1 Ba4 $19) 17... Bxe3 $1 18. Nxa5 Bxf4 $19 {Black has won a pawn, and White's King is still very exposed.}) 16. Ka1 Nc3 $1 17. bxc3 bxc3 18. Bc4 dxc4 19. Rb1 Rb2 $1 20. Rxb2 cxb2+ 21. Kb1 Bb7 22. Rd1 c3 $6 {This move is attractive, but it is not Black's fastest way to win.} (22... O-O 23. f3 Bb4 $19) 23. Qg3 (23. Nb3 {would prolong the game a bit:} 23... Bxe3 24. Nxa5 Bxf4 25. Nxb7 Ke7 26. Nc5 Rc8 27. Nd3 Bd2 $19 {and Black is obviously winning, but it will take some time to break down White's position.}) 23... Bxd4 24. Rxd4 Bd5 25. a4 Ba2+ (25... Qc5 {is winning immediately, threatening ...Qa3-a1#}) 26. Kxa2 b1=Q+ 27. Kxb1 Qb6+ 28. Kc1 Qxd4 29. Bg5 h6 30. Qe3 Qc4 0-1


