1. e4 e6 2. Nf3 {Yet another odd move order!} 2... d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 (4. exd5 {is nothing for Black to fear. After} 4... exd5 5. d4 {White has simply transposed into the harmless Exchange Variation.}) 4... Nfd7 5. d4 {Here we are back in normal French Defense territory once again.} 5... c5 {If White does not take this pawn, Black will capture on d4.} 6. dxc5 Nc6 7. Bf4 Nxc5 8. Be2 a6 {Black gets ready to expand on the queenside with ...b5 and perhaps ...b4 to chase away White's Knight from c3.} 9. O-O d4 $5 {Very aggressive, active play by Black. In theory, this pawn could become a weakness. But right now Black has it adequately defended.} 10. Nb1 b5 11. a3 (11. c3 {would be fine if Black had to take the pawn, but of course he would just win a piece with} 11... d3 $1 $19) 11... Bb7 12. Re1 {Black has been waiting for White to make this move.} 12... Be7 {This move anticipates White's next, completely natural move -- and sets a trap into which White tumbles headlong.} 13. Nbd2 $4 {Missing the point.} 13... g5 $1 14. Bg3 g4 $1 {The point: this Knight has no good retreats!} 15. Nb3 gxf3 16. Bxf3 Qd7 17. Nxc5 Bxc5 18. b4 Be7 19. Qd3 h5 20. h3 Rc8 {A piece down with no threats, White decides to call it a day.} 0-1

