1. e4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. d4 c5 6. dxc5 Nc6 {Black usually plays this move, attacking e5 a second time, before he decides how to recapture on c5.} 7. Bf4 Nxc5 {Although this is not the main line of the Classical French, it is a good move played by strong players.} 8. Qd2 a6 {Preparing for ...b5.} 9. O-O-O $6 {Black's plan of development is very much directed against queenside castling by White. What happens next is rather breathtaking, as the attack unfolds with startling speed.} 9... b5 $1 10. Bg5 Qc7 (10... Qa5 {looks more accurate to me, though perhaps it is objectively about the same, e.g.} 11. Kb1 b4 (11... Bb7 12. Be3 Qc7 13. Ne2 Rc8 14. Ng3 h5 15. Bxc5 Bxc5 16. Qg5 g6 17. Bd3 Be7 18. Qf4 h4 19. Ne2 Rh5 $15 {-0.55/18}) 12. Ne2 Ne4 13. Qe1 (13. Qe3 Bc5 14. Ned4 (14. Nfd4 Qb6 15. Bf4 Nxd4 16. Nxd4 Nc3+ 17. bxc3 bxc3+ 18. Bb5+ axb5 19. Qxc3 b4 $19 {-2.78/18}) 14... Qb6 {and Black has an overwhelming attack.} 15. Ka1 Nxd4 16. Nxd4 Nxg5 17. Qxg5 Bxd4
18. Qxg7 Rf8 19. f4 Be3 $19 {-3.16/18}) 13... Rb8 (13... Nxg5 14. Nxg5 h6 15. Nf3 Bc5 16. Ned4 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Qc7 18. g4 O-O 19. h4 a5 $15 {-0.68/18}) 14. Ka1
Nxg5 15. Nxg5 h6 16. Nf3 Bc5 17. Nf4 O-O 18. g4 Bd7 19. Rg1 Qb6 $17) 11. Qe3 (11. a3 Rb8 12. b4 Nd7 13. Qe3 h6 14. Bf4 Nb6 15. Nd4 Nxd4 16. Qxd4 Rb7 17. Be3
Be7 18. h4 Nc4 19. Bxc4 bxc4 $17 {-0.84/18}) 11... b4 {A key move. Black is chasing the White Knight away from the defense of the e4 square so that his own Knight can go there without being immediately exchanged off.} 12. Ne2 Ne4 {All according to plan.} 13. Bf4 Qa5 {The Queen makes it to the proper square. Now White's a-pawn is under fire.} 14. Kb1 {Protecting a2.} 14... Bc5 $1 {With this move, Black forces White to interpose a Knight on d4 -- otherwise, Black's Knight on e4 will fork White's
Rooks when it takes on f2.} 15. Nfd4 Nxd4 {The point of this exchange of Knights is to pull White's other Knight away from the e2 square so that it will no longer help to defend the critical c3 square, where Black is preparing a sacrifice.} 16. Nxd4 Nc3+ $1 {Black is investing a whole piece for just a pawn, but the returns on this investment are huge.} 17. bxc3 bxc3 {Now Black threatens, among other things, 18...Rb8+ 19.Ka1 Rb2 and mate on a2 cannot be stopped.} 18. Nb3 {White gives back the piece immediately in order to stop the attack. Since the Knight is forking Black's Bishop and Queen, Black's reply is forced.} 18... Bxe3 {The secret of Black's tactical play here lies in the fact that the Bishop on f4 is hanging, which means that Black will regain the sacrificed piece and remain a pawn ahead with the pair of Bishops.} 19. Nxa5 Bxf4 20. Re1 Bd7 {Keeping the White Knight out of c6.} 21. Nb3 a5 22. g3 Bg5 {Black chooses this retreat square because he is planning to play ...Be7, bringing the Bishop back into the game on the queenside.} 23. Nd4 Rb8+ 24. Ka1 Be7 25. Nb5 Bxb5 26. Rb1 {Pinning the Bishop to the undefended Rook -- but
Black has an adequate response.} 26... Bb4 $1 27. a3 Bc4 28. axb4 axb4 29. Rd1 Kd7 {Black's plan is to double Rooks on the a-file and deliver checkmate on a1. Simple -- but unstoppable except at ruinous cost in material.} 30. Kb1 Ra8 0-1

