1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. Nf3 c5 6. dxc5 Nc6 7. Bf4 Nxc5 {There is our slightly unusual recapture. Ultimately, Black would be very happy if this Knight could be stationed at e4. However, at the moment, White's Knight on c3 would simply take it, leaving Black with a weak pawn on e4 when he recaptures. So Black must be patient and keep his plans flexible.} 8. Bd3 Be7 9. O-O O-O (9... Nxd3 {first is also reasonable.}) 10. Re1 Nxd3 {This is a good example of mental flexibility. With White castled kingside, Black does not have a chance for a massive attack. So he takes the Bishop off, which means his own kingside will be more secure since White has been deprived of the strong Bishop.} 11. Qxd3 Bd7 {This move looks so minimal that you might wonder why it is played at all. The first answer is that it frees the c8 square for the Rook on a8. The second answer is that Black has a plan to activate this Bishop on the kingside.} (11... a6 {is also reasonable right
away, for the reasons mentioned in the note to Black's 13th move.}) 12. a3 Rc8 {As advertised.} 13. g3 a6 {It is useful for Black to keep a White Knight out of the b5 square, from which it might have leapt into d6.} 14. h4 f5 15. Rad1 {This move looks a bit careless to me.} (15. exf6 {(en passant!)} 15... Bxf6 {is also possible here. White should try to clamp down on the e5 square, where he has enough pieces to keep Black tied down.}) 15... Be8 $1 {Here is the real point behind ...f5: Black wants to get his bad Bishop out on h5 and perhaps to trade it for a White Knight.} 16. Bg5 Bh5 {Now Black's pieces are beginning to look very active and the White position seems like it has stalled.} 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Rd2 {Black now has several reasonable plans.} 18... h6 (18... f4 {Black could make this push right away. In a few moves, he does it anyway.}) (18... Na5 {This is a reasonable move as well, looking for an outpost for the Knight on c4. White could stop that plan by playing} 19. b3 {But then the Knight on c3 and the pawn on a3 are weakened, e.g.} 19... Bxf3 20. Qxf3 Qxa3 $17) 19. Nd4 Nxd4 20. Qxd4 f4 $1 {Black decides that his best chances lie on the kingside, so he plays to open up lines there.} 21. Nxd5 $2 {White panics. This piece sacrifice is unnecessary and unsound.} 21... exd5 22. Qxd5+ Kh8 {For his piece, White obtains two pawns, a check, and a passed e-pawn. It isn't enough.} 23. e6 Rcd8 24. Qa5 {Only this square works to defend the Rook on d2.} 24... Rxd2 {Black trades down, since his extra piece will be of more value in a simplified position.} 25. Qxd2 fxg3 26. fxg3 Qc5+ 27. Qe3 Qxe3+ {Following the same policy: Black
swaps off anything that might cause him trouble.} 28. Rxe3 Re8 {Black stops the pawn, which he will shortly win. White will then be down a piece for a pawn and should lose, but he is stubborn and makes Black play it out.} 29. Re5 Bd1 30. c3 Re7 {With this move, Black stops the White pawn on the e6 square -- a light square -- and prepares to attack it a second time with the Bishop.} 31. Kf2 Bb3 {As promised. Now the pawn falls.} 32. Ke3 Rxe6 {Taking with the Rook is right because it forces White into an exchange of Rooks. Every exchange of pieces brings Black closer to victory.} 33. Rxe6 Bxe6 34. Kd4 Bd7 {Black gets eady to put the Bishop on c6, where the Bishop and pawn will defend one another. Then Black's King can walk over to g4 and Black can begin to eat the kingside pawns.} 35. c4 Kh7 36. b4 Kg6 37. Ke5 Kh5 38. Kf4 g5+ 39. hxg5 hxg5+ 40. Kf3 Bc6+ 41. Kf2 Kg4 42. c5 {If it were White's move now, White would have to start losing pawns. Black therefore cleverly "loses" a move with his Bishop} 42... Ba4 43. Kg2 Bb5 44. Kf2 Bc6 {This is the same position we had at move 42, but now it is White's turn to move!} 45. a4 Bxa4 46. Kg2 Bb5 47. Kh2 Kf3 (47... Bc6 {also wins easily.}) 48. Kh3 g4+ 49. Kh2 Bc4 50. Kg1 Kxg3 51. Kh1 Kf2 {Black will checkmate White quickly here.} (51... Kf2 52. Kh2 Bf1 53. c6 g3+ 54. Kh1 Bg2#) 0-1

