1. e4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. d4 c5 $1 {The standard pawn chain break.} 6. dxc5 Nc6 7. Bf4 Nxc5 {This is the sideline we are preparing.} 8. Qd2 Be7 9. O-O-O $6 {Castling queenside in this variation is always very risky for White.} 9... a6 $1 10. Qe3 b5 $1 11. Nd4 Bb7 12. Qg3 g6 {Black simply stops the threat to g7. He does not intend to castle.} 13. Be3 Rc8 {This is where the Rook belongs, generating pressure up the half-open c-file.} 14. f4 b4 $1 {The standard maneuver is to push the Knight away from c3, then drop a Knight on e4. Here, Black has other ideas.} 15. Nce2 Na5 {Black aims to drop this Knight on the c4 square.} (15... Ne4 {is also perfectly good.}) 16. Kb1 Qc7 (16... Qb6 {is also good.}) (16... Nc4 {could also be played immediately.}) 17. Qe1 Nc4 18. Nc1 Na4 (18... Ne4 {also looks strong. The truth is, Black's position is just better here, and he has many ways to improve the position of his pieces while White is huddling on his back rows trying not to lose.}) 19. Bxc4 (19. b3 Nc3+ 20. Ka1 Nxe3 {and Black wins a piece since White cannot recapture without losing his Rook on d1:} 21. Qxe3 Nxd1 $19) 19... dxc4 20. Qf2 Qa5 21. Rhe1 Bd5 $1 {Very strong.} (21... c3 $1 {is also very strong.} 22. Ncb3 Qc7 $19) 22. g4 Nxb2 $1 {A piece sacrifice that shatters White's defenses.} 23. Kxb2 Qa3+ 24. Kb1 c3 $1 {White is threatened by mate on b2, and his only defense against that allows a different mate.} (24... c3 25. Nd3 Qxa2+ 26. Kc1 Qa1#) 0-1

