1. e4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 {Even though White has not yet played d4, he will have to do it in a move or two. So Black simply follows the normal pattern of luring the pawn to e5 and preparing to hit back with ...c5.} 4. e5 (4. exd5 exd5 {is a toothless version of the Exchange Variation:} 5. d4 Bg4 6. Bg5 c6 7. Bd3 Bd6 8. O-O O-O $11) 4... Nfd7 5. d4 c5 {Now we are back in the main lines.} 6. dxc5 Nc6 7. Bf4 Nxc5 $5 {Black plays for piece activity rather than aiming to destroy White's last center pawn. For a while, at least, Black will leave his pawn on f7 and play around the central pawn chain.} 8. Bd3 Be7 9. O-O a6 {Queenside expansion is appropriate here to finish the activation of Black's pieces.} 10. Re1 b5 11. a3 Bb7 12. b4 Nxd3 13. cxd3 g5 14. Bg3 h5 15. h3 h4 16. Bh2 Qb6 17. d4 O-O-O {This move should not
even be very surprising. The King is much safer here than he would be on the kingside, where things are about to get intense.} 18. Rc1 Rhg8 {No prizes for seeing what Black has coming next!} 19. g4 {White tries to stop it by getting his own pawn to g4 first. But Black tears through everything in his path.} 19... hxg3 20. Bxg3 g4 $1 {The Rook on g8 needs more scope, and this is the perfect way to get it.} 21. hxg4 Rxg4 {Black has opened a lot of lines against White's King.} 22. Kg2 Kb8 {This could seem like a strange move, but it is actually very logical. Black may want to use his N/c6 at some point in the attack -- perhaps to take a pawn on d4. However, with White's Rook on c1, Black's King would be vulnerable to a devastating discovered check. By moving the King off of the open file, Black ensures that he won't be caught by that kind of nasty surprise.} 23. Ne2 Rdg8 24. Rh1 a5 {This pawn advance works out, but it requires good judgment to see that it will not backfire. Black is attacking on the kingside: keeping queenside lines closed seems like a good idea!} (24... Qd8 {intending ...Qf8 is a safer way to play, bringing more firepower to the kingside.}) 25. bxa5 (25. Rh7 {would be a bit more active. But after} 25... axb4 26. axb4 R4g7 $15 {Black is still calling the shots.}) 25... Nxa5 26. a4 b4 {Now White has to worry about Black's queenside activity, particularly the use of the c4 square for the minor pieces.} 27. Rb1 Ba6 28. Rh7 R4g7 29. Rxg7 Rxg7 30. Nf4 b3 31. Nd3 Rg8 32. Nc1 Bc4 {This is a very unusual state of affairs: Black is threatening to advance his b-pawn, which is in front of his own King -- and pinned!} 33. Nd2 b2 34. Qc2 Ba3 {The Bishops do an amazing job of controling the squares the pawn needs.} 35. Qc3 bxc1=Q 36. Rxb6+ Nb7 37. Qf3 (37. Qxc1 Bxc1 {would leave Black a piece ahead.}) 37... Rh8 {Threatening ...Qh1#} 38. Rb1 Bf1+ 39. Kg1 Be2+ 40. Rxc1 Bxf3 {Black threatens both to capture the Rook on c1 and to deliver checkmate on h1.} 0-1

